As humans, we swim in a small portion of the electromagnetic spectrum that is visible to the human eye, radiating a wavelength we call light. ‚ú® Specialized cells in our eyes are tuned to receive the wavelengths of this narrow band of electromagnetic spectrum. 
The most important characteristic of visible light is color. Nothing you see "has" color. Instead, objects give off light that "appears" to be a color. Color exists only in your mind. 
Light at the lower end of the spectrum having a longer wavelength is perceived as red.üçìLight in the middle of the spectrum, green. ü•í Light at the upper end of the spectrum, violet. üçá
All other colors that we perceive are mixtures of these colors. Three colors that create our reality and determine our history. 
What do we not see? What does this mean for our understanding of reality. Conceptions based on perceptions. It‚Äôs insane that this perception of light and color information forms the basis for our human experience... every judgement we make, the truths we think we have, the faces of those we love, the way we navigate this earth, the pixels on the device you are holding right now... each action we take and every thing we make. So enjoy your the perceptions, question your conceptions and absorb and reflect all the light you can.

Holed up in a cabin in the mountains of Colorado today with my family. It's snowing and I am reflecting on a huge and totally human hope. As a child, Christmas was always preceded by much expectation. So much hope and excitement for even the smallest gifts. These days I'm hoping for something even more tangible but far more reaching. That humanity would awaken to its potential for love and connection; that we would become one. And it may be that the only thing that holds us back from this is our imagination and belief that this is indeed possible. The words of French philosopher Pierre Chardin de Teilhard... truer today than when first penned: "Let us look at the earth around us. What is happening under our eyes within the mass of peoples? What is the cause of this disorder in society, this uneasy agitation, these swelling waves, these whirling and mingling currents and these turbulent and formidable new impulses? Mankind is visibly passing through a crisis of growth. Mankind is becoming dimly aware of its shortcoming and its capacities. And as we said on the first page, it sees the universe growing luminous like the horizon just before sunrise. It has a sense of premonition and of expectation‚Ä¶ The flame must be revived at all costs."
Love is the affinity which links and draws together the elements of the world... Love, in fact, is the agent of universal synthesis. ‚ÄîTeilhard

President Obama addresses world leaders inside the General Assembly Hall including the presidents of China and Russia. The final film I directed entitled "The Story You Are Shaping" will play to close the General Assembly: 11th plenary meeting, 70th session of the United Nations Sustainable Development Summit 2015. Watch live now at webtv.un.org @the_human_story @unitednations Very surreal to be inside this room in this historic moment.

Over the next three days I have the great privilege and responsibility of "speaking" to the largest gathering of world leaders in human history‚Äîthrough images, words and sound. They have converged in New York for the United Nations Sustainable Development Summit and at 3pm EST, the first of a series of seven films I wrote and directed will premiere for world leaders before they begin each of their dialogue as they work to adopt the sustainable development agenda. These films are a declaration of interdependence. A call to honor the rights of all people, everywhere. And to protect the planet, our common home. They address our world leaders as human beings and thus, the message is universal and for all. They are about people and our planet and our interdependence with one another.¬†¬†Much more to share and many to thank and credit in forthcoming posts. You can watch live on http://webtv.un.org @unitednations @the_human_story
Something amazing is happening here in 10 days. Can't wait to share what we have been working on. @unitednations @the_human_story

For the last two nights at Madison Square Garden, the voices of three brave people and one talented poet opened the @dispatchmusic concerts in a film I directed about hunger in America to an audience of thousands. Inspired by Louis, Deb and Danielle and her two kids Ziana and Judah who shared what it feels like to face food insecurity, something 1 in ever 6 Americans experience. Yep, line up six people in America and one of them does not have access to enough nutrition. And for children its worse: 1 out of every 5. Its not because there isn't enough food in America, it's because there isn't enough access and it's solvable. So we are joining these voices and saying, access for all.  Thank you @kingjasminemans for lending your poetry and voice to anchor this film and call for change and to my friends @bradcorrigan, Pete and Chad from Dispatch for giving your stage to talk about this to your fans. Thankful to the @the_human_story team for all your work and of course to Louis, Deb, Danielle, Ziana and Judah for sharing your stories. We're listening. #dispatchhunger

You've heard by now... Today it happened again. A policeman not indicted by a grand jury. This time for the killing of Eric Garner, an unarmed dad from Staten Island. Using an illegal chokehold, the officer was caught on camera and the death was ruled a homicide by the medical examiner. Eric's final words were, "I can't breath". Tonight we marched again to protest. To simply say something is wrong. That things need to change. Here as the police helicopter flew above us, a girl's body is traced in chalk as she lays on the Brooklyn bridge. The actual audio recording of Eric's final words underscores the moment to honor him... "History will have to record that the greatest tragedy of this period of social transition was not the strident clamor of the bad people, but the appalling silence of the good people."- Martin Luther King Jr  #ericgarner #icantbreath #ferguson #nyc

It's hard to imagine justice right now but more than ever this is our collective task. The story of Michael Brown does not begin with the immediate events that led to his death. When we begin the story myopically at the moment of the altercation, it overlooks the deep injustice and wounding which created a systemic minefield of repression for a boy growing up in community and a nation which still has not reconciled the violence of the past. His story thankfully does not end with his death either. Let us submit ourselves to the wisdom of Michael Brown's family who implore us now: "We need to work together to fix the system that allowed this to happen." I am trying to imagine justice together with them in the face of this confusing outcome. A form of justice that works for all people in this nation. I think this statement from Dr. Martin Luther King in last speech before he was killed may point us in the right direction: "In the human rights revolution, if something isn't done, and done in a hurry, to bring the colored peoples of the world out of their long years of poverty, their long years of hurt and neglect, the whole world is doomed...Let us rise up tonight with a greater readiness. Let us stand with a greater determination. And let us move on in these powerful days, these days of challenge to make America what it ought to be. We have an opportunity to make America a better nation." When you imagine justice, what do you see? #ferguson #fergusondecision

Being weighed, yet feeling weightless. 
Filming the vital work of the World Food Programme this week in Tanzania with @wfpusa has allowed me to witness their unparalleled role in solving global hunger. 
Good nutrition to mother and child in the first 1,000 days shapes the life of a child and the fate of a nation. 
In this moment, a girl spins her little sister in a hanging scale. Her weight is being tracked monthly at MCHN Hospital in Makiungu to prevent her from suffering from serious, often irreversible, physical and cognitive damage due to malnutrition. Mother's and children receive WFP supplements and vital nutrients tailored to their needs. This baby is growing well and she is developing as every child should. 
Food is the universal language that unites humanity. Follow @wfpusa and @the_human_story

Almost exactly 10 years ago I landed in Dar Es Salaam and began a journey throughout Africa that continued across the around the world and inspired the founding of @discoverthejourney. I was fearlessly young and beautifully naive. Today as I exited the same airport that served as a gateway to opening myself to seeing and feeling the beauty and suffering of the world, I remember how it all began. The subsequent journeys to overlooked places; asking thousands of questions; meeting and knowing so many people; the courage and humility of the marginalized; the voices of so many brave and resilient children; facing risk and overcoming obstacles; all the learnings along the way. More than anything I learned to embrace the reality that our stories are interconnected--their outcomes interdependent. I want to keep learning, keep loving, adding value wherever I can and participate in the story of humanity hoping that 10 years from today I can reflect on other experiences of beauty, shared pain, captivating stories and more of life to the fullest. To all, I hope you discover your own journey and your place in the journey we are all on together.
